<Base
  title="About — David Oduneye"
  description="Who David Oduneye is — engineer, powerlifter, photographer, writer."
>
  <section>
    <h1>About</h1>
    <div class="prose" style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">
      <p>
        I'm David Oduneye. I studied computer science at Northeastern
        University in Boston, and I've been building things — software and
        otherwise — for as long as I can remember. The first spark was a high
        school programming class, TI-84 calculators and scrappy HTML pages,
        and the feeling of being able to make absolutely anything I wanted. I
        chased that feeling into a career.
      </p>
      <p>
        These days I write software for a living. I care about clean
        architecture, type safety, and systems that are simple enough to
        reason about but robust enough to rely on — strong opinions, loosely
        held. But the code has always been the means. What I'm actually after
        is the same thing that hooked me in that classroom: making things that
        work, understanding them all the way down, and getting a little better
        at it every day.
      </p>
      <p>
        That's also why the gym is the other half of my life. I compete as a
        <a
          href="https://www.openpowerlifting.org/u/davidoduneye"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener noreferrer">powerlifter</a
        >, and powerlifting is the same discipline in a different costume:
        show up, add a little weight, trust the process, let the progress
        compound. When I'm not under a barbell I'm usually out with a camera,
        traveling, or watching films.
      </p>
      <p>
        I write here about all of it — software, strength, and the systems I
        use to keep my life in order. The <a href="/writing">writing</a> is
        the best window into how I think.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2 class="section-label">How I think about software</h2>
    <ul class="entry-list prose">
      <li>
        <strong>Parse, don't validate.</strong> Data gets typed at the
        boundary. After that, the types do the work.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Composition over configuration.</strong> Small pieces that fit
        together beat large pieces with many knobs.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Server-first, client when needed.</strong> Ship HTML. Hydrate
        only what moves.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Layers don't leak.</strong> Routes handle HTTP. Services handle
        logic. Data handles storage. They don't reach into each other.
      </li>
    </ul>
  </section>

